<section xml:id="section-row-red-terminology" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
	<title>row echelon form</title>
	<idx><h>row</h><h>echelon form</h></idx>
	<p>
	a matrix that has the following properties:
	<ul>
		<li>
			if a row has nonzero entries, its first nonzero entry is a one
			(called a <term>leading one</term><idx><h>leading</h><h>one</h></idx>),
		</li>
		<li>
			each leading one occurs in a column that is to the right of the column containing the leading one in the row above it,
			and
		</li>
		<li> zero rows appear below all nonzero rows </li>
	</ul>
	</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>reduced row echelon form</title>
	<idx><h>row</h><h>echelon form</h><h>reduced</h></idx>
	<p>
	a row echelon form matrix that also has the following property:
	<ul> <li>the leading one of each row has all other entries in the column that contains it equal to zero</li> </ul>
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<note><p>
	The acronyms <term>REF</term> and <term>RREF</term> are commonly used for <term>row echelon form</term> and <term>reduced row echelon form</term>, respectively.
</p></note>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
	<title>row reduction</title>
	<idx><h>row</h><h>reduction</h></idx>
	<p> the process of using elementary row operations to reduce a matrix to REF or RREF </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>row equivalent matrices</title>
	<idx><h>row</h><h>equivalent</h></idx>
	<p> matrices where it is possible to obtain one from the other through a sequence of elementary row operations </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>rank</title>
	<idx><h>rank</h><h>of a matrix</h></idx>
	<p> the number of leading ones in the RREF of the matrix </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>leading variables</title>
	<idx><h>leading</h><h>variables</h></idx>
	<p> the variables in a linear system whose columns in the RREF of the augmented matrix contain the leading one of some row </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>free variables</title>
	<idx><h>free variables</h></idx>
	<p> the variables in a linear system that are not leading variables </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>general solution</title>
	<idx><h>general solution</h></idx>
	<idx><h>solution</h><h>general</h></idx>
	<p> a set of parametric equations from which all solutions to a linear system can be obtain by choosing arbitrary values for the parameters </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>homogeneous system</title>
	<idx><h>homogeneous system</h></idx>
	<idx><h>system</h><h>homogeneous</h></idx>
	<p> a linear system in which the <q>equals</q> column is all zeros </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>coefficient matrix</title>
	<idx><h>coefficient matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>coefficient</h></idx>
	<p> the matrix for a linear system but without the <q>equals</q> column </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>trivial solution</title>
	<idx><h>solution</h><h>trivial</h></idx>
	<idx><h>trivial</h><h>solution</h></idx>
	<p> the obvious solution to a homogeneous system obtained by setting all variables to equal zero </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>nontrivial solution</title>
	<idx><h>nontrivial solution</h></idx>
	<idx><h>solution</h><h>nontrivial</h></idx>
	<p> a solution to a homogeneous system that is not the trivial solution </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
